<exercise id="fs-idp91522240">
<problem id="fs-idm94419200">
<para id="fs-idp75942032">Explain why ice, which is a crystalline solid, has a melting temperature of 0 °C, whereas butter, which is an amorphous solid, softens over a range of temperatures.</para>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-idm138844688">
<para id="fs-idm74685056">Ice has a crystalline structure stabilized by hydrogen bonding. These intermolecular forces are of comparable strength and thus require the same amount of energy to overcome. As a result, ice melts at a single temperature and not over a range of temperatures. The various, very large molecules that compose butter experience varied van der Waals attractions of various strengths that are overcome at various temperatures, and so the melting process occurs over a wide temperature range.</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
